  "prompt": "What are some examples of Russian superstitions?",
  "response": "Russian culture is rich with superstitions, many of which are deeply rooted in folklore, history, and traditions. Here are some common examples:\n\n1. **Whistling Indoors**  \n   Whistling inside the house is believed to chase away money and bring financial misfortune. It\u2019s said to \"whistle away\" your wealth.\n\n2. **Sitting on the Corner of a Table**  \n   Sitting at the corner of a dining table is thought to bring bad luck, especially for unmarried women, who may not find a husband for seven years.\n\n3. **Breaking a Mirror**  \n   Breaking a mirror is considered a sign of severe bad luck, often associated with seven years of misfortune.\n\n4. **Returning for Forgotten Items**  \n   If you leave the house and forget something, returning to get it is considered unlucky. To counteract this, Russians often look in a mirror before leaving again.\n\n5. **Knocking on Wood**  \n   To avoid tempting fate or jinxing something, Russians knock on wood three times.\n\n6. **Empty Bottles on the Table**  \n   Leaving an empty bottle on the table is believed to bring poverty or bad luck. Bottles should be removed or placed on the floor.\n\n7. **Giving Even Numbers of Flowers**  \n   Even numbers of flowers are associated with funerals and mourning, so giving flowers in odd numbers is customary for happy occasions.\n\n8. **Shaking Hands Over a Threshold**  \n   Shaking hands or greeting someone while standing on opposite sides of a threshold is considered bad luck. It\u2019s thought to lead to arguments.\n\n9. **Spilling Salt**  \n   Spilling salt is a sign of impending conflict. To counteract this, one must toss a pinch of spilled salt over their left shoulder.\n\n10. **The Black Cat**  \n   A black cat crossing your path is considered unlucky in Russian folklore, just as it is in many other cultures.\n\n11. **Birthday Celebrations in Advance**  \n   Celebrating a birthday before the actual date is believed to bring bad luck or even shorten your life.\n\n12. **Pointing with a Finger**  \n   Pointing at someone with your finger is considered rude and unlucky. Instead, Russians often gesture with their whole hand.\n\n13. **Dreaming of a Tooth Falling Out**  \n   Dreaming of a tooth falling out is often interpreted as a sign of upcoming illness or death of a loved one.\n\n14. **Opening Umbrellas Indoors**  \n   Opening an umbrella inside the house is said to bring bad luck, possibly because it\u2019s seen as tempting fate to make it rain.\n\nThese superstitions are often taken seriously, especially by older generations, and many have practical or cultural explanations tied to historical beliefs and practices.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
